Here's the proper approach using MAUI's lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** — hook into the `Window` lifecycle:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppBackgroundMessage());

    window.Activated += (s, e) =>
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppResumedMessage());

    return window;
}
```

**Messages** (using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm):

```csharp
public class AppBackgroundMessage { }
public class AppResumedMessage { }
```

**In your NoteViewModel:**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject, IRecipient<AppBackgroundMessage>, IRecipient<AppResumedMessage>
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;

    public NoteViewModel()
    {
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.RegisterAll(this);
        RestoreDraft(); // also restore on first load
    }

    public void Receive(AppBackgroundMessage message) => SaveDraft();
    public void Receive(AppResumedMessage message) => RestoreDraft();

    private void SaveDraft()
        => Preferences.Default.Set("note_draft", DraftText);

    private void RestoreDraft()
        => DraftText = Preferences.Default.Get("note_draft", string.Empty);
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Solution |
|---|---|
| **When to save** | `Window.Deactivated` — fires on background/minimize |
| **When to restore** | `Window.Activated` — fires on resume |
| **Where to store** | `Preferences` for small text; `SecureStorage` or file for sensitive/large content |
| **Decoupling** | `WeakReferenceMessenger` keeps `App` and ViewModel independent |

> **Tip:** For large notes, write to a file instead of `Preferences` (which is meant for small values). Use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` for the path.
